Url.Title: Introducing the DSC Q Series
Url.Abstract: Introducing the DSC Q Series The Differential Scanning Calorimeter (DSC) Q Series™ instruments determine the temperature and heat flow associated with material transitions as a function of time and temperature. They provide quantitative and qualitative data on endothermic (heat absorption) and exothermic (heat evolution) processes of materials during physical transitions such as phase changes, melting, oxidation, and decomposition. This information helps the scientist or engineer identify processing and end-use performance.

Url.Title: Calibrating Tzero
Url.Abstract: Calibrating Tzero The DSC Tzero* calibration requires two experiments. The first experiment is done without samples or pans (baseline); the second is performed with large (approximately 95 mg) sapphire disks (without pans) on both the sample and reference positions. Both experiments use the same method beginning with a cell preheat followed by an equilibration at an initial temperature, holding isothermal for 5 minutes, heating at constant rate to a final temperature and holding isothermal for 5 minutes. The range of temperatures should be at least as broad as the desired experimental range. Tzero calibration should be done at relatively high heating rates such as 20°C/min in order to obtain the most accurate calibration of the sensor thermal capacitance and resistance values. Rates of less than 10°C/min are not recommended for Tzero calibration.

Url.Title: Calibrating the T1 Baseline
Url.Abstract: Calibrating the T1 Baseline (T1 Heat Flow) The baseline slope and offset calibration involves heating an empty cell through the entire temperature range expected in subsequent experiments. The calibration program is used to calculate the slope and offset values needed to flatten the baseline and zero the heat flow signal. This calibration is used in the DSC Q20 and Q10, and when the selected heat flow is T1 for the DSC Q2000, Q1000, Q200, or Q100.

Url.Title: Calibrating the DSC Enthalpy (Cell Constant) and Temperature
Url.Abstract: Calibrating the DSC Enthalpy (Cell Constant) and Temperature Calibrating Enthalpy (Cell Constant) This calibration is based on a run in which a standard metal (e.g., indium) is heated through its melting transition. The calculated heat of fusion is compared to the theoretical value. The cell constant is the ratio between these two values. The onset slope, or thermal resistance, is a measure of the suppression of temperature rise that occurs in a melting sample in relation to the thermocouple. Theoretically, a standard sample should melt at a constant heating rate. As it melts and draws more heat, a temperature difference develops between the sample and the sample thermocouple. The thermal resistance between these two points is calculated as the onset slope of the heat flow versus temperature curve on the front of the melting peak. The onset value is used for kinetic and purity calculations to correct for this thermal resistance.

The instrument stores a maximum of 1000 indium calibrations and verifications. However, when the number of calibrations and verifications exceeds 1000, the instrument will continually replace the oldest data point with the newest value. Url.Title: Setting Up a DSC Zero Baseline Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a DSC Zero Baseline Procedure This template can be used to adjust the absolute value of the heat flow baseline to zero mW at the lower and upper temperature limits without requiring the complete Tzero calibration procedure. This template should be used between routine Tzero calibration whenever the offset and slope have drifted from zero. It is not necessary to use this template if the full Tzero calibration is performed.

Url.Title: Setting Up a DSC Ramp Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a DSC Ramp Procedure DSC ramp experiments heat or cool the material at a constant rate. The results obtained are affected by the previous thermal history (often imparted on the material during processing [e.g., extrusion]). Therefore, the results are designated "as received.”

Url.Title: Setting Up a DSC Isothermal Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a DSC Isothermal Procedure DSC isothermal experiments provide an indication of a material's stability at an elevated temperature. The purge gas, which surrounds the material, remains constant or is switched at the elevated temperature to generate a sample-atmosphere interaction (e.g., oxidative stability).

Url.Title: Setting Up a DSC Cyclic Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a DSC Cyclic Procedure DSC Cyclic experiments are used to assess changes in the material as it is exposed to a series of heating/cooling cycles. Multiphase materials (e.g., emulsifiers) often change internally (become less stable) during thermal cycling.

Url.Title: Setting Up a DSC Heat/Cool/Heat Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a DSC Heat/Cool/Heat Procedure DSC Heat/Cool/Heat experiments are designed to erase previous thermal history by heating the material above a transition (e.g., glass transition or melting), where relaxation or molecular rearrangement can occur, then cooling at a known rate before heating again. The first heating curve provides the “as received” information. The cooling imparts a known thermal history. Therefore, any differences observed between similar materials in the second heating curve are related to real internal differences in the materials (e.g., molecular weight) rather than previous thermal history effects.

Url.Title: Setting Up a Conventional MDSC Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a Conventional MDSC Procedure The actual complex temperature/time profile in Modulated DSC® depends on three variables—underlying heating/cooling rate, modulation period, and modulation temperature amplitude. In conventional MDSC experiments, all three variables are operator-selected for best results and the material is evaluated during heating over a temperature range.

Url.Title: Setting Up an MDSC Heat-Iso Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up an MDSC® Heat-Iso Procedure Three variables are adjusted to obtain the desired MDSC temperature profile—the underlying heating, modulation period, and temperature amplitude of modulation. When studying melting events, it is beneficial to adjust these variables so that the minimum instantaneous heating rate achieved is 0°C/minute (isothermal). By not cooling the material at any time during the modulation, the possibility for "artificially" affecting any observed crystallization phenomena is eliminated. More importantly, when the instantaneous heating rate is zero, there is no heat flow associated with heat capacity and, therefore, any heat flow observed at the top of the raw modulated heat flow signal must be the result of kinetic phenomena.

Url.Title: Setting Up an MDSC Quasi-Isothermal Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up an MDSC® Quasi-Isothermal Procedure In quasi-isothermal MDSC experiments the underlying heating rate is zero. However, by selecting a modulation temperature amplitude and period, the material is still exposed to an instantaneous heating rate.

Url.Abstract: DMA Calibration Error - Force/position spike Force for full slide travel is too large. This error can occur during calibration if too much force is required to move the drive shaft (slide) to the top of its range. The cause may be one of the following:

Url.Title: DMA Calibration Error - Frame temperature or air pressure
Url.Abstract: DMA Calibration Error - Frame temperature or air pressure Frame Temperature Wait until the instrument finishes its warm-up period (approximately 30 minutes). The Frame Temperature status on the Signal Display screen will read "OK" when the instrument is ready to be run. Then press Continue to retry the calibration or Exit to abort the calibration.

Url.Title: DMA Calibration Error - Test is running
Url.Abstract: DMA Calibration Error - Test is running You have attempted to start a calibration procedure while a test is running on the instrument.

Url.Title: DMA Calibration Error - Bad analog or drive error
Url.Abstract: DMA Calibration Error - Bad analog or drive error The analog board or drive board did not pass the confidence test.

Url.Title: DMA Calibration Error - Method active
Url.Abstract: DMA Calibration Error - Method active An experiment is already in progress on the instrument. You cannot perform any calibration functions while the method is running.

Url.Title: DMA Calibration Error - Previous step not done
Url.Abstract: DMA Calibration Error - Previous step not done When performing the calibration, the steps must be followed in sequence for proper calibration of the instrument.

Url.Title: DMA Calibration Error - Gain or offset too low
Url.Abstract: DMA Calibration Error - Gain or offset too low This is caused by a problem with the DMA thermocouple calibration circuit.

Url.Title: DMA Calibration Error - Gain or offset too high
Url.Abstract: DMA Calibration Error - Gain or offset too high This is caused by a problem with the DMA thermocouple calibration circuit.

Url.Title: Calibration Aborted
Url.Abstract: Calibration Aborted You have selected to abort the calibration procedure. Press Calibrate to retry this operation. If you change your mind and want to proceed, press Continue. If you want to abort the calibration, press Cancel to close the window and stop the calibration.

Url.Title: File is Not Available
Url.Abstract: File is Not Available The file ___ is not available for download. Use the TA Instruments Advantage CD and completely reload the software. If the error persists, contact TA Instruments for assistance.

Url.Title: Sample and Reference Sizes Not Required
Url.Abstract: Sample and Reference Sizes Not Required The file selected for calibration has sample and reference sizes specified. Zero sizes are expected for this calibration file.

Url.Title: File Needs Sample and Reference Sizes
Url.Abstract: File Needs Sample and Reference Sizes The file selected for calibration has zero sample and reference sizes. Sample sizes are expected for this calibration file.

Url.Title: Must Recalibrate When Heat Flow Changed
Url.Abstract: Must Recalibrate When Heat Flow Changed Changes to this heat flow selection require that you recalibrate cell constant and temperature. Are you sure you want to make this change?

Url.Title: Heat Flow Results Not Optimized
Url.Abstract: Heat Flow Results Not Optimized Heat flow results using this pan type are not optimized. See online help for further details. Are you sure you want to make this change?

Url.Title: File Not Found
Url.Abstract: File Not Found The file named in the command does not exist in the current directory or search path specified, or the filename was entered incorrectly.

Url.Title: Failed to Open File for Writing
Url.Abstract: Failed to Open File for Writing

Url.Title: Error Reading From File
Url.Abstract: Error Reading From File

Url.Title: Error Writing to File
Url.Abstract: Error Writing to File

Url.Title: Not a Valid Macro File
Url.Abstract: Not a Valid Macro File %s is not a valid autoanalysis macro file. The file selected is not a valid TA Instruments Autoanalysis macro file, which needs to be created using the Universal Analysis program. Select a valid file before proceeding.

Url.Title: Exit Without Saving Analysis?
Url.Abstract: Exit Without Saving Analysis? Do you wish to exit without saving the analysis? This is a confirmation message triggered by the attempt to exit the calibration analysis without saving the results. If you wish to proceed without saving the analysis, press OK. If you want to continue the operation and save the analysis, click Cancel.

Url.Title: Failed to Create Object
Url.Abstract: Failed to Create Object A software error has occurred. Make sure the software components are up to date and registered in the NT registry. You may have to reinstall the Advantage software.

Url.Title: Operation Failed. Do Not Reset. Try Again.
Url.Abstract: Operation Failed. Do Not Reset. Try Again. Verify transferred program file failed. You shall not reset your instrument. Please try to send files again.

Url.Title: Failure. Retry Operation
Url.Abstract: Failure. Retry Operation Verify transferred string file failed. You need to retry again. This message is displayed during the downloading of instrument software using the Tools/Instrument Setup wizard. The file transfer (download) was not successful. Do not reset the instrument.

Url.Title: File Backup Done
Url.Abstract: File Backup Done The Backup operation has been completed. This is a confirmation message to let you know that the instrument file backup operation has been successfully completed.

Url.Title: File Already in Use
Url.Abstract: File Already in Use The file you have attempted to load is already being used elsewhere and cannot be accessed. Choose another file.

Url.Title: Instrument Control Message Open File Failure
Url.Abstract: Open File Failure The file you have specified is inaccessible. It may be already in use, or the file format may not be recognized by the program.

Url.Title: Restore Operation Successful
Url.Abstract: Restore Operation Successful The Restore operation has been completed. This is a confirmation message to let you know that the files have been successfully restored to the instrument.

Url.Title: Number of Cycle Markers Incorrect
Url.Abstract: Number of Cycle Markers Incorrect There are an incorrect number of cycle markers in this method for a Tzero calibration. The Tzero calibration is based on two experiments (baseline and sapphire), which are conducted using a very specific method. The expected method was not found (e.g., the number of cycle markers not as expected). Check the method log for these files and conduct one or both of these experiments again using the calibration wizard only. Do not modify the running method during these tests.

Url.Title: Window Already Open on Touch Screen
Url.Abstract: Window Already Open on Touch Screen Platform calibration window already opened on instrument touch screen.

Url.Title: Calibration Data Not Accepted
Url.Abstract: Calibration Data Not Accepted The instrument did not accept the calibration data. Retry the calibration.

Url.Title: Insufficient Instrument Disk Space
Url.Abstract: Insufficient Instrument Disk Space The instrument does not have enough free flash disk space to download a new executable file. Call TA Service.

Url.Title: Invalid Tzero File
Url.Abstract: Invalid Tzero File Invalid Tzero file. The DSC Tzero file is not valid. You will need to either use a valid Tzero file or produce a new file.

Url.Title: Language Does Not Reside in Instrument
Url.Abstract: Language Does Not Reside in Instrument The selected language does not exist in the instrument. You must update module software.

Url.Title: Language Cannot Load - English is Default
Url.Abstract: Language Cannot Load - English is Default Language initialization failed - Program defaulted to English.

Url.Title: Confirm Lid Closure
Url.Abstract: Confirm Lid Closure The instrument is currently running. Are you sure you want to close the lids? The instrument is currently performing an operation and you have selected to close the AutoLid.

Url.Title: Confirm Lid Open
Url.Abstract: Confirm Lid Open The instrument is currently running. Are you sure you want to open the lids? The instrument is currently performing an operation and you have selected to open the AutoLid.

Url.Title: Direct Command Control Error
Url.Abstract: Direct Command Control Error Load Direct Command Control's DLL error! Code %d This is an internal error that is caused because the DCC.dll file was not found.

Url.Title: Must Log In as Master Controller
Url.Abstract: Must Log In as Master Controller This program requires you log in as a master controller. However, One of the controllers on the network is connected as a master already. You need unregister the master on that controller and try to log in again.

Url.Title: Do You Want to Clear Log?
Url.Abstract: Do You Want to Clear Log? Are you sure you wish to clear the log? This message is displayed after you click the Clear Log button on the Instrument Log. It just confirms that you wish to delete all of the entries from the log stored by the instrument.

Url.Title: No More Method Segments
Url.Abstract: No More Method Segments You have reached the maximum number of segments (255) allowed in a method. To add another segment you must first delete a segment to make room.

Url.Title: Method Segment Has Invalid Temperature Limits
Url.Abstract: Method Segment Has Invalid Temperature Limits To correct the problem, edit the invalid temperature value in the method file. See the online help reference to determine the temperature limit applicable to the instrument. Then run the edited procedure.

Url.Title: Method Segment Has Invalid Type
Url.Abstract: Method Segment Has Invalid Type To correct the problem, edit the invalid segment in the method file. See the online help reference to determine the temperature limit applicable to the instrument. Then run the edited procedure.

Url.Title: Not TA Method
Url.Abstract: Not TA Method The method file that you have selected to open is not a valid TA Instruments method file.

Url.Title: Incorrect Method for Instrument
Url.Abstract: Incorrect Method for Instrument The method file selected is not applicable to the instrument (and cell type) installed or the filename may be incorrect. The method file is for a different instrument family. For example, a TGA method file was read by a DSC.

Url.Title: Instrument Type Not Supported
Url.Abstract: Instrument Type Not Supported The instrument type is not supported or the required component is missing for the instrument!

Url.Title: File Not MSDOS Compatible
Url.Abstract: File Not MSDOS Compatible The file selected is not MSDOS compatible in that is does not contain a maximum of eight characters and a three-character extension. Rename the file and try the operation again.

Url.Title: Not a Tzero Calibration File
Url.Abstract: Not a Tzero Calibration File The file you have attempted to load is not a valid Tzero calibration file. If was not obtained using the correct method as generated through the calibration wizard.

Url.Title: Baseline Calibration Not Needed
Url.Abstract: Baseline Calibration Not Needed Baseline calibration is not appropriate for this instrument. This message is displayed when a baseline data file has been read but the selected heat flow signal is not T1.

Url.Title: No Calibration Types Appropriate
Url.Abstract: No Calibration Types Appropriate None of the calibration types are appropriate for this file. This message is displayed if the Select Calibration Type dialog has been displayed but the data file selected does not support any of the allowable calibrations.

Url.Title: File Not Available
Url.Abstract: File Not Available File was not available for download. The file that you have attempted to use cannot be located in the directory specified. Please check the filename and location to make sure the file is present as specified and try the operation again. If this message persists, you will need to use or create a different file for download.

Url.Title: No Sample and Reference Sizes
Url.Abstract: No Sample and Reference Sizes The file selected for calibration has zero sample and reference sizes. Sample sizes are expected for this calibration file.

Url.Title: Close Advantage?
Url.Abstract: Close Advantage Q Series? You have chosen to close this program. If there are any experiments in progress when the program is closed, any data collection to the controller will not be lost.

Url.Title: OLE Initialization Failed
Url.Abstract: OLE Initialization Failed

Url.Title: OLE Failed
Url.Abstract: OLE Failed Ole register drop target failed. This error is displayed when the segment list is not working properly. Close the Thermal Advantage Q Series™ program and restart it.

Url.Title: Download Successful
Url.Abstract: Download Successful Software download successfully completed. Press the OK button to close this program and restart the instrument.

Url.Title: Download Complete. Reset Instrument
Url.Abstract: Download Complete. Reset Instrument Software download successfully completed. Press the reset button on the back of the instrument to complete the process.

Url.Title: Language Selection Successful
Url.Abstract: Language Selection Successful Change of language successfully completed. Press the OK button to close this program and then press the reset button on the back of the instrument to complete the process.

Url.Title: Quench Cooler for Heat Flow T1 Only
Url.Abstract: Quench Cooler for Heat Flow T1 Only Quench Cooler can be used to determine Heat Flow T1 only. This message is displayed if you have selected Quench Cooler as your cooler type and either Heat Flow T4P or Heat Flow T4 as your heat flow selection on the Instrument Preferences/DSC Page. The Quench Cooler can only be used with Heat Flow T1.

Url.Title: Error Software Compatibility Not Checked
Url.Abstract: Error Software Compatibility Not Checked < > not found. Software compatibility between controller and instrument is not checked.

Url.Title: Error Software Compatibility Not Checked
Url.Abstract: Error Software Compatibility Not Checked < > not found. Software compatibility between controller and instrument is not checked.

Url.Title: Rename String File Failed
Url.Abstract: Rename String File Failed Rename string file failed. Do you still want to transfer the program file?

Url.Title: Reset Factory Settings?
Url.Abstract: Reset Factory Settings? All standard settings will be reset to the manufacture default values. Do you want to continue?

Url.Title: Please Reset Instrument
Url.Abstract: Please Reset Instrument Please press the reset button on the back of the instrument to complete the process.

Url.Title: No Calibration Parameter Changes
Url.Abstract: No Calibration Parameter Changes The instrument uses the calibration information to calculate data during an experiment. Therefore, the calibration parameters cannot be changed while a method is running.

Url.Title: Sample File Not Specified
Url.Abstract: Sample File Not Specified A valid filename for the sample data file must be entered into the Tzero filename dialog in order to perform a DSC Tzero calibration. Either create a sample file or locate one. Specify the new file and retry the operation.

Url.Title: Save Calibration Analysis?
Url.Abstract: Save Calibration Analysis? Do you wish to save the calibration analysis? This message is displayed to remind you to save the calibration analysis you have just performed, if desired. You can choose to save the analysis or reject it and the operation will be cancelled.

Url.Title: Select Backup Directory
Url.Abstract: Select Backup Directory Select a Base Backup Directory to Save Instrument Files. Choose a backup directory that will be used to store instrument files.

Url.Title: Select Restore Directory
Url.Abstract: Select Restore Directory This message is displayed when you are performing a service/restore option and you have not specified a directory. The directory specified should match the MAC address of the instrument.

Url.Title: Change X-Axis?
Url.Abstract: Change X-Axis? The curve contains analysis results which will be deleted when this change is made. Do you want to continue to change the x-axis?

Url.Title: Save Cell Constant?
Url.Abstract: Save Cell Constant? The heat flow signal used to generate this calibration file does not match the current heat flow selection. Cell constant and temperature calibration experiments should be performed using the same heat flow as sequent experiments. Do you want to save the cell constant?

Url.Title: Service Menu Selected
Url.Abstract: Service Menu Selected You have just activated the Service menu. You must restart the application for the changes to take effect. This menu item will be removed after 8 hours or if the application is closed. Do you want to proceed?

Url.Title: Verify Shutdown
Url.Abstract: Verify Shutdown Are you sure you want to activate an instrument shutdown? All communication to the instrument will be halted. Select YES to begin this process or NO to cancel operation. Once it is safe to turn off the instrument a message will be posted.

Url.Title: Windows Sockets Initialization Failed
Url.Abstract: Windows Sockets Initialization Failed Windows sockets initialization failed.

Url.Title: Cannot Change Runs
Url.Abstract: Cannot Change Runs You can not change runs while the DSC calibration is in progress. You have attempted to schedule another run while the DSC calibration wizard is in progress. Wait until the calibration is complete before starting another run.

Url.Title: Changes Require Recalibration. Proceed?
Url.Abstract: Changes Require Recalibration. Proceed? Changes to this heat flow selection require recalibration of cell constant and temperature. The current calibration values for these parameters will be reset. Are you sure you want to make this changes?

Url.Title: Not a Valid File
Url.Abstract: Not a Valid File ____ is not a valid file for ____. This message is displayed to let you know that the file you have selected for Tzero calibration is not a valid file for the purpose displayed or for the selected instrument.

Url.Title: Instrument Not Ready
Url.Abstract: Instrument Not Ready The instrument is not ready to start the experiment. Press Start Experiment to restart the experiment.

Url.Title: Parameters Not Matched
Url.Abstract: Parameters Not Matched Parameters of ____ and ____ are not matched! The parameters of the two files listed above do not match. Choose two files that were created using the same instrument and parameters.

Url.Title: Sapphire Sizes Cannot be Zero
Url.Abstract: Sapphire Sizes Cannot be Zero Sapphire sizes cannot be zero. When performing DSC calibration experiments, the sample size used for the sapphire sample cannot equal zero. Enter the sample size and continue.

Url.Title: Calibration is in Progress
Url.Abstract: Calibration is in Progress Calibration is in progress. Do you want to stop the experiment and calibration wizard?

Url.Title: Enter Tzero Baseline File
Url.Abstract: Enter Tzero Baseline File Please enter an existing Tzero Baseline data file. You have the option of reloading previously saved cell resistance and capacitance (Tzero) calibration information. This would be useful in situations where experimental conditions are changed frequently (e.g., daily), but there is no reason to believe the cell itself has changed. Select the desired Tzero baseline calibration file from the displayed file selection window.

Url.Title: Tzero Calibration Error
Url.Abstract: Tzero Calibration Error There has been an error during the calculation of the Tzero calibration values. Repeat the calibration operation.

Url.Title: Cell Constant Reset
Url.Abstract: Cell Constant Reset Cell constant has been reset to one. Are you sure you want to exit the calibration wizard without performing this calibration?

Url.Title: Cannot Perform MDSC Experiments with T1
Url.Abstract: Cannot Perform MDSC Experiments with T1 The T1 Heat Flow signal cannot be used to conduct modulated experiments.

Url.Title: Correction Greater Than 50°C
Url.Abstract: Correction Greater Than 50°C You have tried to save a temperature calibration in which the difference between the observed and the correct temperatures for one temperature calibration point is greater than 50°C. This is not allowed.

Url.Title: Too Hot for Pan
Url.Abstract: Too Hot for Pan XXX °C is too hot for an < > pan. Change either the pan type or the temperature in the Experimental Parameters page.

Url.Title: Transfer Failed
Url.Abstract: Transfer Failed Transferred file failed. You should not reset your instrument. Please try to transfer files again.

Url.Title: Transfer Warning
Url.Abstract: Transfer Warning The file you are sending to the instrument is a critical file. If the transfer fails, the instrument may not run. Please use the Instrument Setup Wizard to transfer the file. Are you sure you want to continue?

Url.Title: Tzero File No Match
Url.Abstract: Tzero File No Match One of the following items does not match with the instrument. You have selected to send a Tzero calibration file to the instrument which doesn't match the listed conditions of the instrument you are sending it to. Check that you have selected the correct file using the Tools/File Utility window.

Url.Title: Tzero Ramp Too Short
Url.Abstract: Tzero Ramp Too Short The ramp was not long enough for a successfull Tzero calibration. The ramp must last for at least X minutes.

Url.Title: Tzero Values are Zero
Url.Abstract: Tzero Values are Zero Tzero slope or offset data is equal to zero. This message is received during the use of the Calibration Wizard for Tzero (Cell Resistance & Capacitance) calibration. The Tzero slope and/or offset results from this calibration are equal to zero. This is not a valid calibration result. Rerun the calibration data again. If the problem persists, call TA Instruments.

Url.Title: Cannot Transfer Tzero Calibration
Url.Abstract: Cannot Transfer Tzero Calibration Unable to transfer Tzero calibration information to the instrument. Please try again.

Url.Title: Unknown Instrument Calibration
Url.Abstract: Unknown Instrument Calibration The data file that you have selected to analyze for calibration purposes was not obtained with the current instrument. Use a calibration file appropriate to the instrument window that you are currently working in.

Url.Title: Instrument Currently Receiving Files
Url.Abstract: Instrument Currently Receiving Files The instrument is receiving files. If you cancel this operation, the instrument will not reboot and run correctly. You must resend the files to instrument BEFORE YOU CAN REBOOT it. Are you sure you want to continue?

Url.Title: Data File Saved
Url.Abstract: Data File Saved The data file will be saved to the destination. If there is a file with the same name, it will be appended a time stamp in its name. Do you want to continue?

Url.Title: Must Assign a Project
Url.Abstract: Must Assign a Project You cannot continue to the next page until a project has been selected. When using this wizard, you must select a Project on this page in order to proceed.

Url.Title: Wrong File for Instrument
Url.Abstract: Wrong File for Instrument The file < > is not for the current instrument type. Do you want to continue?

Url.Title: Inappropriate Files. Transfer Anyway?
Url.Abstract: Inappropriate Files. Transfer Anyway? The files in currently selected directory are not for the instrument. Do you still want to transfer them to the instrument?

Url.Title: Incompatible Software Version
Url.Abstract: Incompatible Software Versions The current version of instrument software is not compatible with the controller. Please go to the Instrument Setup Wizard and download the latest version of instrument software before proceeding.

Url.Title: Password Incorrect. Try Again
Url.Abstract: Password Incorrect. Try Again The password is incorrect! You have to try again. The password as entered is incorrect. Please check the spelling and try again.

Url.Title: Prohibited Under 21 CFR 11
Url.Abstract: Prohibited Under 21 CFR 11 This operation is prohibited by 21 CFR restriction. You cannot perform this operation under the rules covered by 21 CFR 11.

Url.Title: Analysis Limits Error
Url.Abstract: Analysis Limits Error The analysis limits must be between __ and __ °C. The limits used for analysis of this type of data file must fall within the temperature range stated in the message. Select new limits in that range and perform the analysis again.

Url.Title: Incorrect Instrument Type
Url.Abstract: Incorrect Instrument Type Incorrect instrument type chosen in SelectCalType(). The instrument that you have chosen is not compatible with the operation selected. Please choose another instrument.

Url.Title: Slow Communication
Url.Abstract: Slow Communication Either the instrument is too busy, locked-up, or the communication device is too slow.

Url.Title: Press to exit dialog with no changes
Url.Abstract: Press to exit dialog with no changes When you click the Cancel button, the calibration is aborted and the window is closed with no changes.

Url.Title: Press to learn about the dialog
Url.Abstract: Press to learn about the dialog Click the Help button to open the online help for this window.

Url.Title: Press to exit dialog and accept data
Url.Abstract: Press to exit dialog and accept data When you click the OK button, you accept the items chosen or entered on the window and the window closes.

Url.Title: Weight Calibration Out of Range
Url.Abstract: Weight Calibration Out of Range Weight calibration coefficients out of range. You have attempted to enter a weight value, during TGA Weight Calibration, that is either less than 10.0 or greater than 200.00 grams.

Url.Title: Delete Calibration Files?
Url.Abstract: Delete Calibration Files? At least one of the calibration files has not been analyzed or saved. Do you still want to remove files from the list?

Url.Title: Exotherm Values Different
Url.Abstract: Exotherm Values Different The Exotherm values of the two files are different. The two files selected calibration analysis do not have matching exotherm properties. These files cannot be used together for the calibration. Choose two files with similar exotherm properties for calibration purposes.

Url.Title: Cannot Open Calibration File
Url.Abstract: Cannot Open Calibration File The calibration file you have selected cannot be opened. The file may be faulty or it may be of the wrong type. Try opening a different calibration file.

Url.Title: Instrument Did Not Accept Calibration
Url.Abstract: Instrument Did Not Accept Calibration The instrument did not accept the calibration data. Retry the calibration.

Url.Title: Invalid Calibration File
Url.Abstract: Invalid Calibration File The calibration file you have selected is not recognized as a TA Instruments calibration file. Select another file or create a new one.

Url.Title: Calibration File Generated by Wrong Instrument
Url.Abstract: Calibration File Generated by Wrong Instrument Not a < > calibration file. The calibration file you have selected is not valid for the current instrument, it was created for a different instrument. Select a calibration file that applies to the current instrument or create a new file.

Url.Title: Less Than Two Points
Url.Abstract: Less Than Two Points Less than 2 points in calibration. The calibration file selected does not have enough points to allow successful calibration. Either select another calibration file with more than two points or create a new calibration file.

Url.Title: No Calibration Weight
Url.Abstract: No Calibration Weight No calibration weight sizes specified. While performing an SDT Weight Calibration, the second file (with weights) used for this calibration does not have any calibration weight sizes specified and therefore cannot be used.

Url.Title: Data Not Continuous
Url.Abstract: Data Not Continuous The data is not continuous between the selected limits. The data in the selected file used for calibration analysis is not continuous between the two limits that you have selected.

Url.Title: Dual Sample Not Applicable
Url.Abstract: Dual Sample Not Applicable Invalid file. Dual sample file selected for single sample instrument. You have attempted to use a dual-sample file for a single-sample instrument. Make sure that you use a file obtained from a single-sample DSC for this operation.

Url.Title: Not a Sample A File
Url.Abstract: Not a Sample A File The data file is not sample A data. You have attempted to use a sample B file for a sample side A calibration. Make sure that you use a file obtained from sample side A for this operation.

Url.Title: Not a Sample B File
Url.Abstract: Not a Sample B File The data file is not sample B data. You have attempted to use a sample A file for a sample side B calibration. Make sure that you use a file obtained from sample side B for this operation.

Url.Title: Not a Dual Sample File
Url.Abstract: Not a Dual Sample File Invalid file. Dual sample instrument. You have attempted to use a single-sample file for a dual-sample instrument. Make sure that you use a file obtained from a dual-sample DSC for this operation.

Url.Title: No Module Information
Url.Abstract: No Module Information Calibration file contains no module info. The data file that you have selected to analyze for calibration purposes does not contain information specific to the type of instrument that generated the file. You will not be able to use it for calibration purposes. Use a calibration file that contains all of the information needed.

Url.Title: Sample Size Must Be Greater Than 0.0
Url.Abstract: Sample Size Must Be Greater Than 0.0 The file selected for calibration has a sample size of zero. A zero sample size is not valid for this calibration.

Url.Title: Extrapolated Point Out of Range
Url.Abstract: Extrapolated Point Out of Range Extrapolated point is out of range.

Url.Title: Start and Stop Cannot Be The Same
Url.Abstract: Start and Stop Cannot Be the Same Start and Stop Points are the same. The specified start and stop points chosen for your analysis limits are the same point.

Url.Title: Save Calibration?
Url.Abstract: Save Calibration?

Url.Title: Cannot Change Calibration Settings
Url.Abstract: Cannot Change Calibration Settings Calibration parameters can not be changed while an experiment is in progress.

Url.Title: Baseline Sample Size is Nonzero
Url.Abstract: Baseline Sample Size is Nonzero Warning: Baseline sample size is non-zero. The calibration may not be accurate.

Url.Title: Sample Size Must Be Greater Than Zero
Url.Abstract: Sample Size Must Be Greater Than Zero The file selected for calibration has a sample size of zero. A zero sample size is not valid for this calibration.

Url.Title: Sapphire Delta T Signal is Not Correct
Url.Abstract: Sapphire Delta T Signal is Not Correct The Sapphire Delta T signal is not lower than the Baseline Delta T signal value.

Url.Title: Two Unique Filenames Must be Specified
Url.Abstract: Two Unique Filenames Must be Specified When you calibrate the SDT for DSC heat flow or TGA weight calibration, the two files specified cannot be the same.

Url.Title: Calibration Signals Not Found
Url.Abstract: Calibration Signals Not Found Not a valid < > calibration file. Missing signals. The data file that you have selected to analyze for calibration purposes does not contain the signals specific for calibration purposes (for example, you may have a file that was not created in the proper mode) or you have not selected the correct signals to store in the calibration mode. Therefore, you will not be able to use this file for calibration purposes. Use a calibration file that contains all of the information needed.

Url.Title: Calibration Not Complete. Exit Anyway?
Url.Abstract: Calibration Not Complete. Exit Anyway? At least one of the calibration files has not been analyzed or saved. Do you still want to leave this calibration view?

Url.Title: Enter Acceptable Value
Url.Abstract: Enter Acceptable Value Enter a value between XX and XX. Enter the values for the entry field again. The value you have already entered is not within the range shown.

Url.Title: Unsupported Calibration Type
Url.Abstract: Unsupported Calibration Type There is a problem with the program. Please close all windows, exit the program, and restart the program again. If this problem is not resolved, call TA Instruments for service.

Url.Title: Serial Number Incorrect
Url.Abstract: Serial Number Incorrect The calibration analysis results could not be saved because the number of the cell currently installed on the DSC does not match the cell number in the calibration data file used for analysis.

Url.Title: Wrong Cell Type
Url.Abstract: Wrong Cell Type Calibration file is for a different type of cell. The file you have attempted to load does not match the cell type installed on the instrument. Either choose a file that matches the cell type or conduct the experiment again.

Url.Title: Local Communication Queue is Overflowing
Url.Abstract: Local Communication Queue is Overflowing There is no more space in the communication queue. Wait until the system completes the tasks currently in progress, then repeat the operation. This message is caused by slow communication rate between the controller and instrument. If the error persists, call TA Instruments for service.

Url.Title: Confirm Change
Url.Abstract: Confirm Change You must either confirm the change or click Cancel before you can switch to the next page.

Url.Title: No Changes Allowed
Url.Abstract: No Changes Allowed You are not allowed to make any change on the current run. The instrument is running a method. You cannot make changes to the method in progress. You must wait until the method is complete or stop the method in progress.

Url.Title: Not All Data is On
Url.Abstract: Not All Data is On Not all data in range is ON. Some of the data found in the calibration data file was not turned on. This data will not be used in the calibration analysis.

Url.Title: Error Reading Tzero Calibration File
Url.Abstract: Error Reading Tzero Calibration File There is a problem with the Tzero calibration file you have attempted to use. Check the filename and try again. If the error persists, you may need to generate a new file.

Url.Title: Analysis Limits Error
Url.Abstract: Analysis Limits Error Analysis limits must be between ___ and ___. You have exceeded the analysis limits required for this experiment. Please reselect the limits and try again.

Url.Title: File Not Found
Url.Abstract: File Not Found Instrument Control was unable to find the file requested. This may occur if the file was moved to a different location on the computer or if the file was renamed.

Url.Title: Furnace Close at Method End
Url.Abstract: Furnace Close at Method End This message confirms that the furnace will close at the end of the sequence.

Url.Title: Load Macro File
Url.Abstract: Load Macro File The file is not a valid TA Instruments macro file. This can occur if the file was created using a different application and has the extension .mac.

Url.Title: Operation Illegal for Non-Master
Url.Abstract: Operation Illegal for Non-Master This operation is illegal for a non-master controller. In order to make changes to the experiment you must be registered as the master controller of this instrument. If you are not the master controller you may simply view the progress of the experiment.

Url.Title: Apply Setup Changes
Url.Abstract: Apply Setup Changes You have made some change on your setup pages. You need either Apply or Cancel the changes before you can implement other operations.

Url.Title: Internal Message
Url.Abstract: Internal Message This is a message that is internal to the program. If this message persists, contact TA Instruments for service.

Url.Title: Out of Range
Url.Abstract: Out of Range Enter a number between XX and XX. Enter the values for the entry field again. The value you enter must be within the range shown.

Url.Title: Cannot Change Calibration Settings
Url.Abstract: Cannot Change Calibration Settings Calibration parameters can not be changed while an experiment is in progress.

Url.Title: DSC Calibration Wizard Experiment
Url.Abstract: DSC Calibration Wizard Experiment Experiment in Progress This window displays the progress of the active calibration experiment in real time. Start Experiment initiates the experimental run. Once the experiment is started, the Start Experiment key changes to Stop Experiment, allowing you to stop the experiment if a problem occurs. Cancel aborts the wizard. When the experiment is complete, click the Next button to advance to the next step in the calibration process.

Url.Title: Loading a Saved Cell Resistance and Capacitance Calibration File
Url.Abstract: Loading a Saved Cell Resistance and Capacitance Calibration File You have the option of reloading previously saved cell resistance and capacitance (Tzero) calibration information. This would be useful in situations where experimental conditions are changed frequently (e.g., daily), but there is no reason to believe the cell itself has changed. Select the desired calibration file from the displayed file selection window.

Url.Title: DSC Calibration Wizard Resistance & Capacitance Step 1
Url.Abstract: DSC Calibration Wizard Resistance & Capacitance (Step 1) Baseline Run Calibration to obtain the cell resistance and capacitance values involves two experiments. The first is based on heating an empty cell over the same temperature range that will be used in subsequent sample experiments. The first calibration experiment is referred to as the Baseline Run.

Url.Title: DSC Calibration Wizard Resistance & Capacitance Step 2
Url.Abstract: DSC Calibration Wizard Resistance & Capacitance (Step 2) Sapphire Run The second experiment required to obtain Tzero cell resistance and capacitance values involves heating the cell with two equal weight sapphire disks on the sample and reference platforms over the same temperature range and under the same experimental conditions as the previous Baseline Run. Since identical experimental conditions are required, you will not be prompted to enter that information again. You only need to weigh and enter the weights of the sapphire disks.

Url.Title: DSC Calibration Wizard Constant & Temperature
Url.Abstract: DSC Calibration Wizard Cell Constant & Temperature (Step 3) Cell Constant Setup The second phase of calibration involves determination of the cell (enthalpy) constant and the x-axis temperature calibration. This calibration is usually performed using indium and the same ramp rate, purge gas, and pan type as subsequent sample experiments. Cell constant calibration should be performed after a Tzero calibration.

Url.Title: DSC Calibration Wizard Constant & Temperature Run
Url.Abstract: DSC Calibration Wizard Constant & Temperature Run (Step 4) Cell Constant Run This window allows you to enter the remainder of the experimental conditions for the Cell Constant calibration.

Url.Title: Heater PID Method Segment
Url.Abstract: Heater PID Method Segment The Heater PID method segment is used to change the performance of the instrument furnace during the execution of a thermal method. PID stands for Proportional, Integral, and Derivative, the three modes of traditional temperature control. The Heater PID segment specifies the control coefficients for each mode of temperature control.
